Synchronous programming is when code is executed sequentially line by line. Each statement must be completed before moving on to the next one.

Asynchronous programming allows multiple things to happen at the same time without waiting for a task to complete before starting another one.

Here's an example of synchronous programming:

```javascript
console.log("Start");

function syncTask() {
  for (let i = 0; i < 1000000000; i++) {}
}

syncTask();

console.log("End");
```

In this example, the `syncTask()` function takes a long time to complete because it performs an operation that iterates over one billion times. When we run this code, "Start" gets printed first and then nothing happens until after ten seconds when "End" is finally printed.

Now let's look at asynchronous programming:

```javascript
console.log("Start");

function asyncTask() {
  setTimeout(() => console.log("Async Task Done"), 2000);
}

asyncTask();

console.log("End");
```

In this example, the `asyncTask()` function uses a `setTimeout()` method to delay its execution by two seconds. When we run this code, "Start" gets printed first and then immediately after that "End" is also printed.

After 2 seconds have passed (or when an asynchronous operation completes), `"Async Task Done"` will be logged on the console without blocking any further tasks from being executed simultaneously with other codes in our program.

